### Technicalities of Redirects: Hard vs. Soft

The note also specifies: "Use this template only on [hard redirects](/Wikipedia:Soft_redirect) – for soft redirects use `{{Soft redirect with Wikidata item}}`." This refers to the underlying technical implementation of redirects on Wikipedia.

A [hard redirect](/Wikipedia:Soft_redirect) is the most common type. When you navigate to a page that is a hard redirect, your browser is immediately and automatically sent to the target page. The URL in your address bar changes to reflect the destination. It's a seamless, almost invisible transfer. The original page content for a hard redirect is typically just `#REDIRECT [[Target Page]]`.

A [soft redirect](/Wikipedia:Soft_redirect), in contrast, does not automatically send your browser to the target. Instead, it displays a message on the page informing the user that the content has moved or is available elsewhere, often with a link to the destination. The URL in the address bar remains unchanged. Soft redirects are generally used for content that has been moved to another Wikimedia project (like [Wiktionary](/Wiktionary) or [Wikisource](/Wikisource)) or for very specific circumstances where an immediate, automatic jump isn't desired. The template `{{Soft redirect with Wikidata item}}` would be used on such a page to explicitly link it to its [Wikidata](/Wikidata) entry while presenting the soft redirect message.

Since "Elman network" is a standard, automatic redirect to a section within the English Wikipedia, it is, by definition, a [hard redirect](/Wikipedia:Soft_redirect). The instruction about `{{Soft redirect with Wikidata item}}` is therefore a general guideline for redirect management, not a description of this specific page's nature. It's an internal note for editors, a detail you probably didn't need to know, but now you do. You're welcome.

